From: nix-wasm <eric@codebutler.com>
Subject: [PATCH] busybox: timeout — private argv with -pPID before operands (#35)

Applies on top of 0004 (which spawns timeout's watcher child clone-with-a-fn).

busybox NOMMU `timeout` spawns a watcher child that re-execs itself as the
grandchild with an extra `-pPID` arg (so the grandchild knows which pid to kill
after the timeout), then the parent execs PROG. Stock busybox builds the re-exec
argv by overwriting the SHARED argv: `argv[optind] = "-pPID"`, giving
`["timeout","SECS","-pPID"]`, and relies on (a) a real vfork's exact
suspend-until-exec ordering and (b) glibc getopt PERMUTING the late `-pPID`
option past the `SECS` operand.

Neither holds on the wasm/NOMMU guest:
 - The watcher is spawned with clone(CLONE_VM|CLONE_VFORK), which shares argv
   like vfork; the mutate-in-child / restore-in-parent dance does not survive
   the port.
 - musl's getopt does NOT permute: with argv `["timeout","SECS","-pPID"]` the
   leading operand `SECS` stops option scanning, so `-pPID` is never parsed and
   the grandchild runs with parent==0. It then treats `-pPID` as PROG and dies
   with `timeout: can't execute '-p50'`, so the timeout is never enforced
   (issue #35 — NOT the async-SIGALRM/signal hang it was first filed as; the
   kernel async-signal path is proven good by .#sigalrm-test/.#kill-wake-test).

Fix: the clone child builds a PRIVATE argv copy (never touches the parent's, so
the parent's exec of PROG is correct) and inserts `-pPID` BEFORE the operands —
`["timeout","-pPID","SECS",PROG...]` — so musl getopt parses it regardless of
permutation. The grandchild then has parent!=0, jumps to its watch loop, and
kills PROG after the timeout.

diff -ruN a/coreutils/timeout.c b/coreutils/timeout.c
--- a/coreutils/timeout.c
+++ b/coreutils/timeout.c
@@ -57,9 +57,20 @@
 static int timeout_child(void *arg)
 {
 	struct timeout_child_args *a = arg;
-	a->argv[a->optind] = xasprintf("-p%u", (unsigned)getppid());
-	a->argv[a->optind + 1] = NULL;
-	bb_daemonize_or_rexec(0, a->argv);
+	/* Build a PRIVATE argv for the watcher re-exec; don't mutate the parent's
+	 * (CLONE_VM shares it). Insert "-pPID" BEFORE the operands: musl's getopt
+	 * does NOT permute options past the first non-option (glibc does), so the
+	 * stock layout ["timeout","SECS","-pPID"] leaves -p UNPARSED on the wasm
+	 * guest — the watcher then runs with parent==0, re-execs PROG="-pPID"
+	 * ("can't execute '-pNN'") and never enforces the timeout (issue #35). */
+	int argc = 0;
+	while (a->argv[argc])
+		argc++;
+	char **cargv = xzalloc((argc + 2) * sizeof(cargv[0]));
+	cargv[0] = a->argv[0];
+	cargv[1] = xasprintf("-p%u", (unsigned)getppid());
+	memcpy(cargv + 2, a->argv + 1, argc * sizeof(cargv[0]));
+	bb_daemonize_or_rexec(0, cargv);
 	return 0; /* not reached (bb_daemonize_or_rexec _exits this child) */
 }
 #endif
